TI Tranexamic Acid During Anterior Cruciate Ligament Reconstruction Reduced
   Drained Blood Volume on Day 1 and Hemarthrosis Up to Day 15 but Did Not
   Improve Clinical Outcomes at 3 Months
SO JOURNAL OF BONE AND JOINT SURGERY-AMERICAN VOLUME
LA English
DT Editorial Material
AB Question: Does administration of tranexamic acid (TXA) during anterior cruciate ligament reconstruction (ACLR) reduce intra-articular effusion and improve clinical outcomes?
   Design: Randomized (allocation concealed)*, blinded (patients, surgeons, and postoperative outcome assessor), controlled trial with 3 months of follow-up.
   Setting: 1 clinical center in Italy.
   Patients: 80 patients 18 to 45 years of age (mean age, 31 years; 79% men) who had ACL ruptures and were scheduled for ACLR. Exclusion criteria were treatment with drugs that interfere with coagulation or TXA clearance; concomitant extra-articular anterolateral procedures; multiligament injuries; coagulative disorders; renal impairment; thrombophilia; or history of thrombotic disease, ACLrevision surgery, seizures, or surgery onthe affected knee. 100% of patients completed follow-up.
   Intervention: Patients were allocated to intravenous (IV) TXA, 15 mg/kg in 100 mL of saline solution (n = 40), or 100 mL of saline solution (control) (n = 40), 20 to 30 minutes before tourniquet release during surgery. Transtibial single-bundle hamstring autograft ACLR using standard double-anterior arthroscopic access, in which the graft was fixed proximally using the RIGIDFIX ACL Cross Pin System and MILAGRO Advance Interference Screws (DePuy Mitek) for tibial fixation, was performed. A tourniquet was used and released at the end of surgery. Cefazolin was administered 30 minutes before surgery for short-term prophylaxis, postoperative analgesic comprised ketorolac and dexibuprofen, and low-molecular-weight heparin was administered beginning at 8 hours postoperatively. Patients were discharged on postoperative day (PD) 1 if their medical condition allowed.
   Main outcome measures: The primary outcome was volume of drained blood on PD 1. Secondary outcomes included operative time; patellar circumference and hemarthrosis grade on PD 1, PD 7, and PD 15 and at 3 months after surgery; and clinical outcomes (range of motion, quadriceps strength, pain, International Knee Documentation Committee [IKDC] subscores, and Lysholm score) at 3 months.
   Main results: The TXA and control groups did not differ for operative time (45.0 vs. 40.8 minutes, p = 0.07) or any IKDC subscores (p > 0.65) at 3 months; other outcomes are shown in Table I.
   Conclusion: In patients having ACLR, TXA reduced drained blood volume on PD 1 and hemarthrosis up to PD 15 but did not improve clinical outcomes at 3 months.
