AU Sullivan, JP
AF Sullivan, Jaron P.
TI In ACL Reconstruction with Patellar Tendon Autograft, Adductor Canal
   Nerve Blockade Reduced Quadriceps Function Deficits Compared with
   Femoral Nerve Blockade, but Did Not Differ for Postoperative Pain
SO JOURNAL OF BONE AND JOINT SURGERY-AMERICAN VOLUME
LA English
DT Editorial Material
AB Question: In patients having anterior cruciate ligament (ACL) reconstructionwith patellar tendon autograft, what are the effects of femoral nerve blockade (FNB) compared with adductor canal nerve blockade (ACB) on quadriceps function and postoperative pain?
   Design: Randomized (unclear allocation concealment), blinded (outcome assessors), controlled trial with 6 months of follow-up.
   Setting: Orthopaedic surgery department at the University of Texas at Houston.
   Patients: 86 patients 15 to 50 years of age (mean age, 23 years; 55% men) who were undergoing ACL reconstruction with patellar tendon autograft by a single surgeon. Exclusion criteria were revision ACL reconstruction, ACL repair, multiple-ligament reconstruction, or full-thickness cartilage defects preventing adherence to the postoperative rehabilitation protocol. 91% of patients completed follow-up.
   Intervention: Patients were allocated to ultrasoundguided FNB, 0.2% ropivacaine, 30 mL, with clonidine, 100 mu g, using a 22-gauge 40-mmProBloc II (Kimberly-Clark) insulated needle below the inguinal ligament (n = 42), or ultrasound-guided ACB, 0.2% ropivacaine, 15 mL, with clonidine, 100 mg, using a 22-gauge 80-mm ProBloc II insulated needle at the midthigh (n = 44). All patients had anatomic single-bundle ACL reconstruction with autologous bone-patellar tendon-bone graft from the ipsilateral knee, followed by a standardized weight-bearing rehabilitation protocol (cryotherapy plus a progressive strengthening, balance, and agility program) supervised by a physical therapist.
   Main outcome measures: The primary outcome was quadriceps muscle activation deficit measured at 24 hours, 2 weeks, and 4 weeks. Other outcomes included postoperative pain and morphine equivalent units used during the post-anesthesia care unit (PACU) stay, and adverse events and knee function at 6 months.
   Main results: Quadriceps muscle activation deficit was greater in the FNB group than the ACB group at 24 hours and 2 weeks, but not 4 weeks (Table I). Groups did not differ for pain ormorphine equivalent units during the PACUstay (Table I). At 6 months, groups did not differ for knee function, but more patients in the FNB group had knee extension loss (asymmetric deficit >5 degrees) than in the ACB group (21.1% vs. 5.0%, p = 0.026).
   Conclusion: In ACL reconstruction with patellar tendon autograft, ACB reduced quadriceps function deficits and postoperative adverse events (e.g., knee extension loss) compared with FNB, but did not differ for postoperative pain.
